{[%evp 0,128,19,19,29,9,0,-5,33,-20,6,-15,0,-3,81,51,76,60,55,64,62,50,54,56,
59,43,56,47,47,25,47,14,58,52,37,31,34,-2,4,2,-18,-21,-26,-40,-41,-36,-38,-47,
-22,-37,-12,-63,-63,-54,-63,-61,-21,-92,-87,-86,-51,-86,-86,-86,-86,-102,-96,
-94,-99,-120,-115,-106,-88,-112,-114,-117,-108,-116,-131,-119,-117,-117,-107,
-117,-112,-107,-111,-105,-106,-108,-11,-88,-111,-128,-132,-187,-183,-191,-170,
-179,-300,-425,-426,-836,-981,-981,-1014,-1057,-678,-816,-1012,-1011,-1011,
-1012,-1012,-1012,-1413,-1914,-2142,-1032,-2142,-2446,-2446,-1954,-2431,-29963,
-29964,-29965,-29966,-29967,-29968] In the first couple of games, we shall
take a look at Black's dream scenario. This scenario usually happens when
Black manages to comfortably carry out the advance ...b6-b5. The first
important position in this example arises after Black's 18...b5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Nf3 Qb6 7. e3 Qc7 8. b3 b6 9. Bb2
Bb7 10. Be2 a6 11. O-O Be7 12. Rac1 d6 13. Rfd1 Nbd7 14. Ng5 Rc8 15. Qb1 Qb8
16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 O-O 18. Ng5 b5 $1 {This is the most typical idea in the
Hedgehog. By deflecting the c4-pawn, Black actually gets better central
control.} 19. cxb5 axb5 {[%csl Bd6,Bb5,Ba2,Bb3][%cal Bb5b4,Bd6d5] This pawn
structure will often appear in your Hedgehog games. If White does not have
something concrete at his disposal, this structure tends to be favourable for
Black. In general, our thematic moves are ...d6-d5 (gaining space in the
centre) and ...b5-b4, fixing the queenside. That's exactly what happened in
this game.} 20. Nf3 d5 21. Qd3 b4 {The structure is already fixed. Black
practically has an extra pawn. Additionally, the white knight is now forced
into an unfavourable position.} 22. Na4 Ne4 23. Nd4 {White tries to exploit
the only drawback in Black's position - the c6-square. Obviously, Black has
enough resources to address this issue.} Ndc5 {[%csl Ba4,Ba2][%cal Ba8a2] A
very nice move. By exchanging the a4-knight, Black will be ready to put
pressure on the backward a2-pawn.} 24. Nxc5 Nxc5 25. Qb5 {This move forces the
transition into an endgame which is favourable for Black. Nevertheless, Black
is better anyway. The next couple of moves is quite logical.} Qxb5 26. Nxb5 Ra8
27. Bd4 Rfc8 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ba8a5] Suddenly, the b5-knight is in danger.
White should now reckon with the threat of ...Ra5.} 28. Bxc5 $2 {After this
unfortunate move, White's position is lost.} ({The most precise defence would
have been} 28. Rc2 {when after} Ra5 29. a4 bxa3 30. Nxa3 Rxa3 31. b4 f6 32. f4
Kf7 33. bxc5 Ra4 $15 {[%cal Ga4c4,Bc8c6,Bh7h5,Bf7g6,Bg6f5,Be6e5] Black still
retains his practical chances due to the vulnerable c5-pawn. A possible idea
is to proceed with ...h7-h5 followed by ...Kg6-f5. In such a case, White
should always reckon with the threat of ...e6-e5.}) 28... Bxc5 29. g3 {White
can no longer keep the material balance.} ({The natrual} 29. Rc2 $2 {will be
met by} Rab8 30. Nd4 Bxd4 31. Rxc8+ Rxc8 32. exd4 Rc2 $19 {with a winning rook
endgame.}) 29... Rxa2 30. Nd6 Rc7 31. Nb5 Rc6 32. Ra1 Rxa1 33. Rxa1 Bf8 $19 {
Black has a winning advantage.} 34. Ra7 g6 35. Kg2 Bc5 36. Rb7 Rb6 37. Rxb6
Bxb6 38. Nd6 f5 39. Kf3 Kf8 40. Ke2 Bc5 41. Nb7 Be7 42. Na5 Bd6 43. f4 Ke8 44.
Nc6 e5 45. Nxe5 Bxe5 46. fxe5 Kd7 47. Kd3 Ke6 48. Kd4 g5 49. h3 h5 50. h4 g4
51. Kc5 Kxe5 52. Kxb4 d4 53. Kc4 dxe3 54. Kd3 f4 55. b4 fxg3 56. Kxe3 Kd5 57.
Ke2 Kc4 58. Kf1 Kxb4 59. Kg2 Kc4 60. Kxg3 Kd3 61. Kh2 Ke4 62. Kg3 Ke3 63. Kg2
Kf4 64. Kh2 Kf3 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

