{[%evp 0,94,28,24,24,-32,-7,-7,19,18,26,0,13,34,33,6,73,32,30,25,-2,-5,-7,3,4,
-5,1,12,9,-7,2,-24,-19,-14,-18,-7,-6,-7,-22,-6,-6,-13,0,-10,-4,-7,11,-10,5,-9,
-4,11,0,0,17,16,30,13,5,17,15,69,-17,-17,4,0,0,0,-14,-29,-30,-35,-25,-25,-27,
-23,-25,-33,-25,-25,-26,-26,-26,-26,-26,-26,-25,-29,-29,-26,-43,-41,-27,-32,
-33,-33,-31] This example is a good illustration of how to fight for ...b6-b5
when White is trying to prevent it.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5.
Nxd4 a6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bd2 b6 10. Bf3 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Qxb7
12. Qf3 Qxf3 13. Nxf3 d6 14. Rfd1 Nbd7 15. Kf1 {This is the first critical
position. Since the advance ...d6-d5 leads to IQP position which is favourable
for White, Black should by playing for ...b6-b5. The first question is how to
arrange the rooks. Black played} Rab8 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Bb6b5,Bf8d8] which is
the most logical continuation. In this kind of position, the rooks are very
well placed on b8 and c8. The idea is to support the advance ...b6-b5. At the
same time, with the move ...Rfc8, Black takes under control the important
c6-square. On the other hand, the d6-pawn is only visually weak. In case of
necessity, Black can always protect it by means of ...Ne8.} 16. Nd4 {The most
logical move. White not only stops ...b6-b5, but also tries to make use of the
c6-square.} ({For didactic purposes, let's take a look at the neutral} 16. h3 {
In this case, Black should start with} Rfc8 {[%csl Bc6][%cal Bb2b3] taking the
c6-square under control and provoking the weakening b2-b3.} ({The immediate} 
16... b5 $2 {is premature in view of} 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nd4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal
Bd4c6] when it's difficult to deal with the double threat - Nc6 and Ndxb5.
Always pay attention to the c6-square in this kind of position.}) 17. b3 b5 18.
cxb5 axb5 {[%csl Bc3,Bb3,Bb8,Bc8] In my opinion, Black is already slightly
better. If allowed, he will proceed with ...b5-b4 followed by ...d6-d5, thus
getting the dream endgame. We can now see how important is that we have
provoked the advance b2-b3. Not only the c3-knight is vulnerable but also
after ...b5-b4, White will have a backward pawn on a2.}) 16... Rfc8 17. b3 g6 {
In Hedgehog, we have plenty of time to make generally useful moves such as ...
g7-g6.} 18. e4 Nc5 {Putting pressure on e4 with this move is quite typical for
the Hedgehog.} ({Another very important thematic idea is} 18... Ne5 19. f3 Nc6
{[%csl Bd4] Remember this important maneuver. Black wants to exchange the
d4-knight in order to execute the advance ...b6-b5. A possible follow-up would
be} 20. Nxc6 Rxc6 21. Rac1 ({If White decides to radically stop ...b6-b5 by
playing} 21. a4 {[%csl Bc4,Bb3,Ba4][%cal Bf6d7,Bd7c5] Black's typical idea is}
Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5] Whenever you see the move a2-a4, always try to bring your
knight to c5. This is the best way to exploit White's vulnerable queenside.}
22. Ke2 Nc5 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Bb3b4,Bc5d7] Black's idea is to provoke b3-b4. In
such a case, the c4-pawn will be quite vulnerable.} 23. b4 $2 {[%cal Bc5b3]
White plays into Black's hands.} ({Better is} 23. Rab1 {[%csl Be5,Bc3,Bb3]
[%cal Be7f6,Bf6e5,Bf7f5] Even now, however, Black has a promising position.
The white rook is tied to the defence of the b3-pawn. Black can consider
putting some pressure by means of ...f7-f5 followed by ...Bf6-e5.}) 23... Nd7 {
[%csl Bc4][%cal Bb8c8,Bd7e5]}) 21... h5 {[%csl Bg6][%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,
Bh2h3] In Hedgehog endgames, whenever you have time, always consider gaining
space on the kingside. Otherwise, White can consider doing so if he has the
possibility.} ({A typical tactical mistake would be} 21... b5 $2 22. cxb5 axb5
23. Nd5 {In the database, you can see many games where White executed this
simple tactical idea.} Rxc1 24. Nxe7+ Kf8 25. Nxg6+ hxg6 26. Rxc1 $18 {White
enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 22. Ke2 ({Another typical manoeuvre is} 22. Ne2
Kf8 23. Nd4 {Once again, White makes it difficult for Black to execute the
advance ... b6-b5. A possible follow-up would be} Rc7 24. Ke2 Ke8 25. Nc2 {
[%cal Gc2b4] The knight is heading to b4 in order to force one of the rooks
into a passive position.} Nd7 {This is the typical reaction. Black immediately
brings his knight to c5.} ({Note that after} 25... b5 26. cxb5 axb5 27. Nb4 {
White is usually slightly better. Black should reckon with the vulnerable
b5-pawn and c6-square.}) 26. Nb4 Nc5 27. Bf4 Rd8 28. h3 f5 $132 {This advance
often allows Black to reduce White's central control.}) 22... Kf8 ({Once again,
the direct} 22... b5 $2 {does not work in view of} 23. cxb5 axb5 24. Nd5 Rxc1
25. Nxe7+ Kf8 26. Nxg6+ fxg6 27. Bxc1 $18 {when White is winning.}) 23. Be1 b5
{Finally, this advance becomes possible.} 24. cxb5 axb5 {[%cal Bb5b4,Bd6d5]
Black is ready to get his dream position by means of ...b5-b4 followed by ...
d6-d5. This could happen after} 25. Bd2 b4 26. Na4 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 d5 28. exd5
Nxd5 {[%csl Bb4,Bb3,Ba2][%cal Bg6g5,Bh5h4,Bf7f5,Bf8f7,Be7d6,Be6e5,Bf7e6] with
a very thematic advantage for Black. He is practically playing with an extra
pawn. After consolidating, he can consider expanding in the centre and on the
kingside.}) ({Another possibility is} 18... b5 19. cxb5 axb5 20. Ndxb5 Nxe4 21.
Nxe4 Rxb5 {[%csl Bd6,Ba2,Bb3] This position, however, is quite double-edged.
Black should play very actively in order to compensate for White's queenside
passers.}) 19. f3 Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 20. Ke2 Ne5 21. Be1 ({If White tries to
win a kingside space with} 21. g4 {Black can react by means of} g5 {securing
the e5-knight and preventing White from gaining space.}) 21... h5 {As we know,
this move always fits well in Black's strategy.} 22. Rac1 Kg7 ({In this
position, Black can play} 22... Nc6 {as well. A possible follow-up will be} 23.
Nxc6 Rxc6 24. Bg3 f5 {with enough counterplay.}) 23. Bf2 Bf6 24. h3 {[%cal
Gf3f4] By taking the g4-square under control, White prepares the advance f3-f4.
} g5 $1 {Once again, securing the e5-knight with this typical move works very
well for Black.} 25. Be3 h4 26. Rc2 {[%csl Bd6,Be7,Be5,Bh2,Bg3][%cal Bf6e7,
Bf6e5,Be5a1,Bb2b3]} Ng6 27. Kf1 Kh6 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Bf6e5]} 28. Nde2 Be5 {
[%cal Gb6b5] Black managed to obtain a very promising position. He can already
consider ...b6-b5.} 29. Bd4 b5 30. Bxe5 Nxe5 31. cxb5 axb5 32. Rxd6 Nxb3 33.
axb3 b4 34. Rdd2 bxc3 35. Rxc3 Rxc3 36. Nxc3 Rxb3 {[%cal Be5g6,Bg6f4,Bh6g6,
Bg6f6,Bf6e5]} 37. Nd1 Ng6 38. Kf2 Nf4 39. Ne3 Kg6 40. Rc2 f6 41. Rd2 Kf7 42.
Rc2 Ke7 43. Rd2 Rc3 44. Ng4 f5 45. exf5 exf5 46. Ne3 Ke6 47. Rc2 Rxc2+ {
1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

