{The position on the diagram is very similar to the previous example. Now, we
will see that even if White manages to achieve everything he wants, Black's
position remains playable. At this point, Black started with} 14... a6 {
which is quite typical for such positions.} ({Having studied the previous game,
we can say that the alternative} 14... Nc6 $5 {[%cal Bf8c8,Ba8b8,Ba7a6,Bb6b5]
is quite playable as well. This move is designed to fight against Nd4. At the
same time, Black can start preparing the advance ...b6-b5 by means of ...Rab8
and ...Rfc8.}) 15. Nd4 {Dorfman immediately seizes the opportunity to play
this important prophylactic move.} Rc8 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Ba8b8]} 16. b3 Nbd7 {
Although there is nothing wrong with this classical move, I would prefer to
develop the knight via c6.} ({More precise would have been} 16... Nc6 $5 17.
Nxc6 Rxc6 {[%cal Gb6b5] when it will be easier for Black to execute the
advance ...b6-b5.}) 17. Rfd1 g6 18. Kf1 Nc5 19. Ke2 Nfe4 {Positionally
speaking, this move is quite logical. By exchanging one of the knights, Black
makes easier the advance ...b6-b5.} 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Be1 {[%cal Bf2f3,Be3e4,
Be1g3,Be4f6,Bf6e8] White is preparing to target the d6-pawn by means of f2-f3
followed by e3-e4 and Bg3.} Rc5 $6 {Played with the intention to support the
advance ...b6-b5. At the same time, however, the rook is vulnerable on c5.} ({
I would have played} 21... h5 {when after} 22. f3 Nf6 {Black has a solid
position.}) 22. f3 Nf6 23. Bb4 Rc7 24. Nc2 $1 {Very nice played by Dorfman. He
wants to further improve the position with e3-e4 and Ne3.} Ne8 25. e4 {/\Ne3,
><c4,><d5} Rac8 26. Ne3 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Bg4g5,Bf3f4,Be2f3,Bh4h5]
Even though Black's position is rather passive, White does not have many
constructive ideas. Obviously, the d6-pawn cannot be utilized. Therefore,
White should try to create a second weakness on the kingside. A possible idea
is f3-f4 followed by Kf3, g2-g4-g5, and h2-h4-h5.} ({The immediate} 26. g4 {
will be met by} d5 $10) 26... h5 $1 {Once again, this is the most precise
continuation.} 27. g3 f5 {We have already seen this thematic move.} 28. Ba3 b5
29. cxb5 axb5 30. Rxc7 Rxc7 31. Bb4 Ra7 32. a3 fxe4 33. fxe4 Nf6 $10 {Black
has enough counterplay. Later on, the game ended in a draw.} 34. Kf3 Kf7 35.
Bxd6 Bxd6 36. Rxd6 Rxa3 37. e5 Nd5 38. Nxd5 exd5 39. Rf6+ Kg7 40. Kf4 Rxb3 41.
Kg5 Re3 42. Rxg6+ Kf7 43. Rf6+ Ke7 44. Kf4 Re2 (44... Re4+ 45. Kf5 $14) 45. Rd6
Rf2+ {Hansen,Cu} 1/2-1/2

