{Sometimes, the advance ...d6-d5 is designed to activate our pieces, even at
the price of a temporary pawn sacrifice. Even though such cases are more
common in the middlegame, we can often see this scenario in the endgame as
well. The following game by Pantsulaia is a typical illustration. In this
position he played} 18... d5 $1 {which is the most precise continuation.} 19.
exd5 ({After} 19. cxd5 Bc5 $1 20. Nce2 (20. Be3 $2 e5 $19) 20... exd5 21. exd5
Nxd5 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge5d3] Black is better in view of the superior activity of
his pieces. If allowed he will proceed with ...Ne5 followed by ...Nd3.}) 19...
Bc5 20. Be3 exd5 21. Nf5 $6 {In my view, this is a very risky decision.} ({
More natural would have been} 21. cxd5 g6 {[%cal Gc5a3] This is a generally
useful move. Black takes the important f5-square under control and is ready to
play ...Ba3 under favourable circumstances.} ({In case of} 21... Ba3 22. Nc6
Bxc1 23. Rxc1 $44 {White has sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) 22. d6
Bxd6 23. Nce2 Nd5 24. Rxc7 Rxc7 25. Bf2 Ba3 $15 {In this symmetrical position,
White is slightly better in view of his more active pieces. This is a typical
scenario in the positions arising after the advance ...d6-d5.}) 21... Bxe3+ {
This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence -} 22. Nxe3 d4 23. Nf5 dxc3
24. Ne7+ Kf8 25. Nxc8 Rxc8 26. Rxc3 Nc5 27. Rd1 Ke7 $17 {Even though things
are far from simple, Black's material advantage gives him decent winning
chances. Later on, Pantsulaia managed to take the point home.} 28. Re3+ Ne6 29.
Re5 a5 30. g3 Rc6 31. Kf2 h5 32. h3 g6 33. f4 h4 34. g4 Rc5 35. Rxc5 bxc5 36.
Ke3 g5 37. fxg5 Nxg5 38. Rh1 Nfe4 39. Kf4 Nf2 40. Rh2 Kf6 41. Ke3 Ngxh3 42. Kf3
Ke5 43. Rg2 Ne4 44. Ke3 Nhg5 45. a3 h3 46. Rb2 Nf6 47. Kf2 Nxg4+ 48. Kg3 h2 49.
Rb1 Ne4+ 50. Kg2 Nef2 {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

