{Sometimes, Black manages to execute both ...b6-b5 and ...d6-d5. This
operation is usually connected with a pawn sacrifice and is designed to
activate the pieces.} 21... b5 $1 22. cxb5 d5 $1 23. e5 (23. exd5 Nxd5 24. Nxd5
Rxd5 25. Rxc8+ Qxc8 26. Qe2 Rxd1+ 27. Qxd1 axb5 28. a4 bxa4 29. bxa4 Qc3) 23...
Nd7 24. Qe2 (24. bxa6 Nxe5 25. Qe2 Qa7+ 26. Kg2 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc6b8]}) (24.
f4 Qa7+ 25. Kg2 axb5 26. Qxb5 Nc5 {[%cal Gd5d4] with sufficient compensation
for the pawn, for example:} 27. b4 Ne4 28. Nxe4 Rxc1 29. Rxc1 Qe3 $1 30. Qc5
Qxe4+ 31. Kh3 Ra8 (31... Qf5+ 32. Kg2 Qe4+) 32. Rc2 g5 $132) 24... Rc5 $1 {
[%cal Gd8c8]} 25. a4 (25. bxa6 Rdc8 26. Qe3 Qxa6 27. f4 Qb6 {[%cal Gc5c3]} 28.
Kg2 Qa5 29. Na4 Rc2+ 30. Kh3 R8c7 $132 {[%cal Gd5d4]}) 25... Rdc8 26. Qe3 Qb8
$1 {The beginning of manoeuvre which allows Black to win back the pawn.} 27. f4
Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gc5c3]} 28. Kg2 axb5 (28... Rxb5 $2 29. Nxd5 $1 $18) 29. Kh3 $6 {
Missing Black`s reply.} (29. axb5 Qa5 30. Ne2 {was sufficient for maintain the
balance.}) 29... R5c6 $1 30. Qxb6 (30. Qf3 bxa4 31. Nxa4 Qb4 32. Rxc6 Rxc6 $15)
30... Nxb6 31. a5 Rxc3 32. axb6 $6 (32. Rxc3 $1 Rxc3 33. axb6 Rc6 34. Rc1 Rxb6
35. Kg4 {[%cal Gh2h4] with very good chances for a draw.}) 32... b4 $1 33. Kg4
(33. Rxc3 bxc3 34. b7 Rb8 35. Rd3 c2 36. Rc3 Rxb7 37. Rxc2 Rxb3 38. Kg4 Kh7 39.
h4 $140 $2 h5+ $1 40. Kh3 d4 41. Rc7 Rb5 $1 42. Rxf7 d3 43. Ra7 d2 44. Ra1 Rd5
45. Rd1 Kg6 46. Kg2 Kf5 47. Kf3 Rd3+ 48. Ke2 Rxg3 49. Kxd2 Kxf4 $19) 33... Kh7
$1 34. Rxc3 bxc3 35. Rc1 $2 {This loses.} (35. Kf3 c2 36. Rc1 Rc3+ 37. Kg4 Rxb3
38. Rxc2 Rxb6 39. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] and it seems that Black hardly can make
progress.}) 35... d4 36. Kf3 d3 37. b7 d2 $1 38. bxc8=Q dxc1=Q 39. Qc4 Qd1+ {
0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

