{Sometimes, in Hedgehog structures, Black exchanges his c4-pawn in order to
take the one on c4. The evaluation of the arising symmetrical endgames is
mainly based on the activity of the pieces. Let's take a look at an
instructive example. In this typical position, Black played} 13... d6 {This
move marks the beginning of a forced sequence -} 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxd6 Bxd6
16. Rxd6 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rxc4 18. Rad1 {[%csl Bc3,Bf6,Ba3][%cal Bg7g5,Bg5g4,
Bf6e4,Ba2a3,Bb6b5,Bb5b4] Even though the position looks completely equal, one
should handle it with care. Both sides will be trying to penetrate via the
open files. For example, White will try to prepare f2-f3 followed by eihter
e2-e4-e5 or g3-g4-g5. After driving the f6-knight back, he can already play
Rd7. At the same time, Black can try to bother the white knight by means of
the advance ...b6-b5-b4. Objectively speaking, White's plan is a bit easier to
accomplish.} g6 {Even though this move is not a mistake, I find it a bit
passive.} ({Having in mind White's idea of winning space on the kingside, I
would have played} 18... g5 {[%cal Bg5g4] intending to expand even further
with ...g5-g4. A possible follow-up would be} 19. f3 {[%cal Be2e4,Bg3g4,Bh2h4]}
g4 20. R1d4 Rfc8 {when Black has enough counterplay. White cannot expand on
the kingside.}) 19. f3 Rc5 20. R1d4 Rfc8 21. Rd8+ {This is the most active
continuation.} ({The attempt of gaining a kingside space with} 21. g4 {is well
met by} h5 22. h3 hxg4 23. hxg4 g5 {when Black has nothing to worry about.}) (
21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Rxe4 R8c7 {[%cal Bc5c2]}) 21... Kg7 22. e4 g5 {Finally, Van
Wely opts for this typical move.} 23. Kf2 R8c7 24. Ra8 {This move allows Black
to activate his most problematic piece.} ({More accurate would have been} 24.
Ke3 $14 {when it's not so easy for Black to create counterplay.}) 24... Nd7 $1
{[%cal Gd7e5] Van Wely immediately seizes the opportunity. The knight is going
to e5. The following semi-forced sequence seems natural.} 25. Ra4 Ne5 26. R8xa7
Nd3+ 27. Ke2 Rxa7 28. Rxa7 Nxb2 $11 {The endgame is equal.} 29. Ra3 Nc4 30. Rb3
Na5 31. Ra3 Nc6 32. Ke3 b5 33. Ne2 b4 34. Ra6 Rc2 35. f4 g4 36. Rb6 Rc5 37. Kd2
h5 38. Nc1 Nd4 39. Nd3 Rc2+ 40. Ke3 Nf3 41. Nxb4 Rc3+ 42. Nd3 Nxh2 43. Rb1 Ra3
44. Ra1 f6 45. f5 Nf3 46. fxe6 Ne5 47. Rd1 h4 48. gxh4 g3 49. h5 g2 50. h6+
Kxh6 51. Kf2 Rxa2+ 52. Kg3 Nxd3 53. e7 Ra8 54. Kxg2 Nf4+ 55. Kg3 Nh5+ 56. Kg4
Re8 57. e5 Rxe7 58. exf6 Nxf6+ 59. Kf5 Kg7 60. Rg1+ Kf7 61. Rf1 {1/2-1/2 The
game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

