{Sometimes, carrying out the advance c4-c5 is far from simple. Let's take a
look at such an example. In this position, White played} 14. Bf4 {By putting
pressure on d6, White wants to provoke the move ... Ne5.} Ne5 {Obviously, this
is Black's best reaction.} ({After} 14... e5 15. Bg5 {[%csl Bd5] White has an
obvious advantage in view of the weak d5-square.}) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Bg5 {
[%csl Be6,Be5][%cal Ba2a3,Bb2b4] Now, we can see a slightly different version
of this structure. It will be very difficult for White to execute the advance
c4-c5. Black's best strategy is to prevent even the advance b2-b4. Usually,
Black is ready to exchange the rooks in order to reduce White's pressure on
the d-file. On the other hand, he tries to keep the queens as well as the
minor pieces for the purposes of the kingside counterplay. Even though the
e-pawns are doubled, Black's kingside counterplay shouldn't be underestimated.
Under favourable circumstances, he can start advancing his kingside pawns.}
Rfd8 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Bh4 {[%cal Bf2f3,Bh4f2,Be3e4] A clever
move. White is planning to proceed with f2-f3 followed by Bf2 and eventually
e3-e4. In this structure, the bishop is optimally placed on the diagonal g1-a7.
} h6 20. f3 g5 21. Bf2 Bc6 22. a3 a5 $1 {This is the right approach to the
position. Black should do everything possible to stop the advance b2-b4.} 23.
Qd3 Qc7 {Once again, Black opts for the correct decision.} ({Without queens,
the counterplay is very problematic. For example, after} 23... Qxd3 24. Bxd3
Kf8 25. Bc2 Ke8 26. Kf1 Kd7 27. Bg3 Bd6 28. e4 Kc7 29. Nd1 Nd7 30. Be1 Bc5 31.
Ke2 Bd4 32. b4 axb4 33. axb4 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defence. Even
though the position is objectively holdable, White can play forever.}) 24. e4
Nd7 25. Bd1 Nc5 26. Qd2 {White is getting ready for the advance b2-b4.} Kf8 {
This move seems to be a bit passive.} ({The most precise continuation would
have been} 26... Be8 {with the idea to answer} 27. b4 {with} axb4 28. axb4 Na6
{when White cannot keep the flexibility of his queenside structure.}) 27. Bc2 (
{Even better would have been} 27. b4 Nb7 28. Na2 Be8 29. Be2 axb4 30. axb4 Nd8
31. Nc1 Nc6 32. Nd3 $14 {with a small but stable advantage.}) 27... Ke8 {
Even though Black adopted a slightly passive strategy, he managed to hold the
position.} 28. Be3 Bd7 29. Kf2 Bc8 30. Ke1 Bd7 31. Kd1 f6 32. Kc1 Nb7 33. Qe2
Nd6 34. Bd3 Nb7 35. Kb1 Bc5 36. Bc1 Bd4 37. Nb5 Bxb5 38. cxb5 Ke7 39. Qc2 Qxc2+
40. Kxc2 h5 41. Bd2 h4 42. h3 Bf2 43. Bc4 Kd6 44. a4 Bc5 {1/2-1/2 The game is
a draw.} 1/2-1/2

