15... Qb7 {this seems to be the most reasonable continuation for Black} (15...
Nbd7 $2 16. Nd5 $1 exd5 17. cxd5 Nc5 18. b4 $16 {1-0 Zoltek,T (2335)-Tompa,J 
(2420)/Lodz 1979/(50)}) (15... Qd8 {can be justified in the event of} 16. Ne4
$6 (16. e4 $1 Nbd7 17. Qe2 {followed by f2-f4}) 16... Rac7 {for example:} 17.
Nc2 (17. Ng5 Qd7) 17... Ne8 $1 {avoiding the exchange of knights and keeping
more possibilities for counterplay} 18. g4 b5 19. Ne3 bxc4 20. bxc4 (20. Nxc4
d5) 20... h6 21. Rd3 Nd7 22. Rcd1 Rc6 23. Rb3 Nf8 $5 (23... Nef6 24. Nxf6+ Bxf6
25. Bxf6 Nxf6) 24. Kh1 Ng6 25. Rb7 Rb6 26. Rxb6 Qxb6 27. Bd4 Qb4 28. Kg1 Nh4
29. Qg3 Qb7 30. f3 Ng6 31. Kf1 Bh4 $1 32. Qg1 $2 (32. Qh3) 32... Nf4 33. Nxd6
$2 Nxd6 34. Be5 Nxe2 (34... Nh3 $1 35. Qg2 Nf2 $19) 35. Kxe2 Nxc4 36. Nxc4 Qb5
37. Rc1 Rxc4 38. Rxc4 Qxc4+ 39. Ke3 Qxa2 40. Kd3 Qd5+ {0-1 Debarnot,R (2380)
-Ljubojevic,L (2615)/Las Palmas 1975}) 16. Qxb7 (16. e4 Nc6) 16... Rxb7 {
Black`s chances are not worse, for example:} 17. f3 Nc6 $1 (17... Nbd7 $6) 18.
Ba3 (18. Nxc6 Rxc6 19. e4) 18... Na7 $5 (18... Nxd4 19. Rxd4 d5 20. Bxe7 Rxe7
21. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Ge7c7]} 22. Nxd5 Rxe2+ 23. Kf1 Rxc1+ 24. Kxe2 Nxd5 25.
Rxd5 Kf8) 19. Nc2 $6 (19. e4 Rbc7 $140 20. Bb4) 19... d5 $1 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 21.
Ne3 Rec7 22. Na4 Rc6 23. Rb1 dxc4 (23... b5 24. Nb2) 24. bxc4 b5 25. cxb5 $6 {
this exchange activates Na7} (25. Nb2 g5 26. Rbc1) 25... Nxb5 26. Kf2 g5 $1 {
in addition to the control over c-file Black gains space on the kingside} 27.
Rb4 Kg7 28. h4 h6 29. Rh1 $6 (29. Rd2) 29... R8c7 30. hxg5 hxg5 31. Ra1 $6 (31.
Rd1) 31... Rd6 32. Nb2 (32. Rc4 $5 Rxc4 33. Nxc4 Rc6 34. Nab2) 32... Nd5 33.
Nxd5 $6 (33. Rc4) 33... Rxd5 34. Rc4 Rxc4 35. Nxc4 Nc3 $1 {threatening Rd4} 36.
Ke1 Rd4 37. Ne3 Ra4 38. a3 Nb5 39. Nc2 g4 $1 {Karpov takes the chance to
improve his position on the kingside} 40. fxg4 Rxg4 41. Kf2 f5 42. Kf3 Kf6 43.
Rd1 Rc4 44. Ne3 Ra4 45. Nc2 e5 {Black`s play in this ending is very
instructive - step by step he improves the position of his forces when White`s
defensive task is not easy in a practical game because of weaknesses on both
wings and more active black pieces} 46. Kf2 Ke6 47. Rd3 Rc4 48. Ne3 Rc3 $5 {
in a knight ending White`s a-pawn can be more vulnerable} 49. g4 $2 (49. Rxc3
Nxc3 50. Kf3) 49... f4 50. Rxc3 Nxc3 51. Nc2 e4 $1 52. a4 $2 (52. e3 $2 f3 $19)
(52. Nb4 a5 53. Nc6 a4 54. Na5) 52... Nxa4 53. e3 f3 54. Nd4+ Ke5 55. Nc6+ {
0-1 Pfleger,H (2545)-Karpov,A (2695)/Montilla 1976} (55. g5 Nc5 $19) 55... Kd6
56. Nd4 Nc3 57. g5 Ke5 $19 {0-1 Black wins.} *

