{The position on the diagram was reached in the game Georgiev, Ki - Roiz, M.
Now, instead of the passive 21...Kf8, Black should have played} 21... b5 $1 ({
The alternative} 21... Ne4 {is playable as well. In this structure, the rook
endgames are usually pretty safe.} 22. Nxe4 Rxe4 23. Rhd1 ({It turns out that
the e4-rook is not as problematic as it might seem at first glance. For
example, the attempt to restrict it by means of} 23. b3 {will be answered with}
Rg4 24. g3 Rc2+ 25. Rd2 Rxd2+ 26. Kxd2 Rg6 27. Rc1 Rd6+ $11 {with complete
equality.}) 23... Rc2+ 24. R1d2 Rec4 25. Rd8+ Kh7 26. R8d7 Rc7 27. Rxc2 Rxc2+
28. Kf3 f6 29. b4 a5 30. Rd6 Ra2 31. Rxb6 Rxa3 32. bxa5 Rxa5 $11 {The draw is
obvious.}) 22. Rhd1 ({The tactical justification behind 21...b5 can be seen in
the line} 22. Nxb5 Ne4 {[%cal Gc4c2] with the terrible threat of ...Rc2. Black
is winning on the spot.}) 22... b4 23. axb4 Rxb4 24. Rd8+ Rxd8 25. Rxd8+ Kh7
26. Rd2 Kg6 27. f3 e4 $132 {Black has sufficient counterplay.} *

