{[#] This position was reached in the game Kobalia - Khismatullin.} 26... a5 $1
{A typical way of exploring White's overextended queenside.} 27. bxa5 {White
is forced to decide on the pawn structure.} ({Another interesting possibility
is} 27. b5 {In this case, I found the following sequence -} Bxa3 28. Na4 Qb8
29. Nxb6 Bxg2 30. Kxg2 Qxb6 31. c5 Bxc5 32. Nxc5 Qxc5 33. Qd8+ Kg7 34. Qxa5 Qc2
$132 {Engine analysis shows that Black has enough counterplay in this position.
}) 27... bxa5 28. a4 Bc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7b4] Black is ready to achieve
stability on the dark squares by means of ...Nd7 followed by ...Bb4.} 29. Nb5
$6 {This passive move hands Black the advantage.} ({The position was calling
for energetic play. Therefore, a better solution would have been} 29. c5 Nd7
30. Bb5 Nxc5 31. Nxc5 Bxc5 32. Bxc6 Qxc6 33. Qd8+ Kg7 34. Qxa5 Qd6 {[%cal
Gc5b4]} 35. Qb5 Bb4 36. Na2 Qd1+ 37. Qf1 Qxa4 38. Nxb4 Qxb4 $15 {Even though
Black is symbolically better, the position is a draw.}) 29... Nd7 30. Qa1 Bb4
$17 {Black already enjoys a stable advantage.} *

