1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3
Bb7 9. f3 d6 10. Be2 Be7 11. Rc1 O-O 12. O-O Nbd7 13. b4 {This is a completely
different concept by black. The idea is to prevent White's typical play on the
queenside with a4-a5 and Nb3xa5.} Rfc8 14. Qd2 Qd8 15. Rfd1 Rab8 16. Kh1 $6 {
This is a good place for the king if Black chooses a setup with the queen on
b8 and the bishop on c7. In this position, it's not really an improvement of
the king's position, to say the least.} h5 $1 {Preparing different strategic
ideas: Ideally h5-h4-h3, to open the diagonal for the b7-bishop, but also
vacating h7 for an eventual Nh7 and Bf6, Bg5 or g7-g5.} 17. Bf2 Ne5 18. Na4
Nfd7 19. Qe3 $2 Bg5 $1 20. f4 Bh6 $19 {Black had a winning position, but White
managed to create complications and in the end reach a draw.} 21. b5 Ng4 22.
Bxg4 hxg4 23. Bg3 Ra8 24. Nxe6 fxe6 25. Rxd6 Qe8 26. Nxb6 Nxb6 27. Qxb6 Qxb5
28. Rd8+ Kf7 29. Qxb5 axb5 30. Rd7+ Kg8 31. Rxb7 bxc4 32. Rc3 e5 33. f5 Bd2 34.
Rc2 Rxa3 35. Bxe5 Bh6 36. g3 Re3 37. f6 gxf6 38. Bxf6 Rxe4 39. Kg2 Rce8 40. h4
Re2+ 41. Rxe2 Rxe2+ 42. Kf1 Re3 43. Kg2 Re6 44. Bd4 1/2-1/2

