1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Qc7 6. a3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Be3
Be7 9. Rc1 Ne5 10. Be2 Ng6 11. O-O b6 12. f4 O-O 13. b4 Bb7 14. Bd3 Rac8 15.
Nb3 d6 16. Qe2 Rfe8 17. h3 {This is one of Karpov's rare experiments with the
Sicilian. White has an impressive space advantage all over the board, offering
Black the latent possibility of using the weaknesses left behind by the pawn
moves. For the time being, everything is safely defended, but we will see that
White can become vulnerable on either the dark or the light squares.} Nd7 {
Clearing the bishop's diagonal.} 18. Qf2 Ba8 19. Rc2 Qb8 20. Rfc1 Bh4 {A
slightly annoying move, inviting White to weaken the long diagonal.} 21. g3 {
All the queen retreats have small drawbacks.} (21. Qf3 {exposes the queen to}
f5 $11) (21. Qe2 {runs into} e5 22. f5 Nf4 $11 {This is the first moment when
we see the alternation of moves on the light and dark squares.}) (21. Qd2 {
keeps f4 well defended and the queen safe, but allows} Bg3 {, planning ...
e6-e5. And if} 22. Ne2 Bh4 $11 {, White does not have anything better than
returning with the knight to c3.}) 21... Bd8 {In view of the next move, this
may seem like a loss of time. But I believe that Karpov intended to maintain
some sort of dialogue between his bishop and the knight on b3.} ({More
concretely, if} 21... Bf6 22. Na4 b5 $2 {White has} ({Safer is} 22... Bd8) 23.
Ba7 Qb7 24. Na5 $18) 22. Nd2 Bf6 {After the knight retreat, the bishop is not
needed on d8 anymore.} 23. h4 $5 {As we will see, a double-edged plan,
slightly weakening the dark squares.} ({Karpov probably intended to meet} 23.
Na4 {with} b5 {Here both sides retain reasonable play:} 24. Nb6 (24. cxb5 Rxc2
25. Rxc2 axb5 26. Nc3 Bxc3 $1 27. Rxc3 e5 28. f5 Ne7 {offers Black a solid
position with pressure on e4 and chances to open the centre with ...d6-d5.})
24... Nxb6 25. Bxb6 Bc6 26. h4 Nf8 {, followed by ... Nd7. The game remains
tense. Black cannot take on c4 yet, as this would expose his queenside.}) 23...
h6 $1 {Not only stopping the enemy pawn on h5 but also clearing the h7-square
for the knight.} 24. h5 Ngf8 25. g4 {An aggressive but apparently committal
move, as after ...e6-e5 Black is likely to get control over g5. And yet, the
real commitment consisted of the advance of the h-pawn.} (25. Be2 {allows} Bxc3
26. Rxc3 Nf6 27. Bf3 e5 {, with good counterplay.}) ({Or if} 25. Ndb1 {,
preparing to meet ...Bxc3 with Nxc3,} Nh7 {, followed by ...e6-e5 soon. White
would have to either concede the g5-square or endure the pressure on e4.})
25... Nh7 $1 {Still preparing ... e6-e5.} (25... e5 $6 {is premature due to}
26. f5 $1 Nh7 27. Nf3 {, and Black cannot keep the piece control over g5. For
instance} Ng5 28. Nxg5 Bxg5 29. Bxg5 hxg5 30. Qe3 f6 31. Be2 Qc7 32. Rd2 Red8
33. Kf2 $16 {The black knight does not have the f6-square, which allows White
to invade the d5-square at his convenience. Besides, h5-h6 followed by Rh1 is
a permanent threat.}) 26. e5 $2 $19 {Torre panics after realising the
positional danger cast by ...e6-e5. But there was no simple way to maintain
control:} (26. Nf3 Bxc3 $1 27. Rxc3 Nhf6 {loses a pawn.}) (26. Qg2 $3 {exposes
the queen along the long diagonal.} d5 $1 ({Here Black can answer with the
typical b5 or d5!} 26... e5 $2 27. g5 $1) (26... Bxc3 $6 27. Rxc3 e5 28. g5 $1)
(26... b5 $1 27. cxb5 Rxc3 28. Rxc3 Bxc3 29. Rxc3 axb5 30. Rc1 d5) 27. g5 hxg5
28. fxg5 Be5 {, with unclear play.}) (26. Qg3 {exposes the queen in a
different way.} e5 $1 27. g5 $2 exf4 $1) 26... dxe5 27. g5 exf4 ({Only not} 
27... hxg5 $2 28. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 29. fxg5 Be7 30. Qxf7 $18) 28. Bxf4 Be5 (28...
Nxg5 $5 29. Bxb8 Nh3+ 30. Kf1 Nxf2 31. Kxf2 Rxb8 $19) 29. g6 fxg6 30. hxg6 Bxf4
31. gxh7+ Kh8 32. Rf1 Rf8 33. Be4 Ne5 34. Qg2 Nxc4 0-1

