1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. Nc3 c5 7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4
Bc5 9. Nb3 (9. Nf3 $5 {is the main alternative.}) 9... Nc6 10. Bd3 Be7 ({
If Black does have more ambitious plans for the c5-outpost and the d4-square,
then he can opt for} 10... d6 $5 11. O-O O-O $13) 11. f4 {Seizing space in the
center.} (11. Bf4 $5 d6 12. O-O Ne5 13. Be2 O-O 14. Nd2 $14 {is likely to
reach a line from the English Opening with typical Hedgehog lengthy
maneuvering ahead.}) 11... d6 ({It will be exciting to see practical examples
with} 11... a5 $1 $146 {- a typical method for harassing Nb3.} 12. Be3 (12. e5
Ng4 13. Qe2 h5 $132) 12... Ng4 13. Bg1 a4 14. Nd4 ({the timid} 14. Nd2 {
may lose control over the whole complex of central dark squares after} Bc5 $36)
14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 e5 16. fxe5 Bc5 17. Bxc5 bxc5 18. Nxa4 Bc6 {Indeed, there
is nothing wrong with taking the e5-pawn, but the text leaves an extra option
to capture it with the queen.} 19. Nc3 O-O $44) 12. O-O {White may prefer to
develop his ?c1 at first:} ({Relatively slow is} 12. Qe2 Nd7 13. Be3 Nc5 $13 {
Fedoseev - Bocharov, Sochi 2017}) (12. Be3 $5 O-O (12... a5 {is aimless here
in the view of} 13. Qe2 $16 {and White is comfortably regrouping his minor
pieces}) ({so is with the knight jump to the g4-square, but the original} 12...
g5 $5 {will remind of it -} 13. f5 exf5 14. Nd4 $44) 13. O-O-O $36) 12... Nd7 (
{Here seems to be the last reasonable moment for the advance} 12... a5 $5 13.
Qd1 (13. Be3 $6 Ng4) (13. Na4 Nd7 14. Be3 Nc5) 13... O-O 14. Be3 a4 15. Nd4 (
15. Nd2 d5 16. exd5 exd5 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qh5+ Kg8 20. Qxd5
Qxd5 21. Nxd5 Rad8 $44) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Nd7 {and Black can claim
compensation for the sacrificed pawn after} 17. Nxa4 e5 18. Be3 exf4 19. Bxf4
