{Let me start with two games of mine, in which the Maroczy bind has been
combined with an aggressive plan with castling to the long.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
e6 3. c4 b6 4. a3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. Nc3 c5 7. e4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Nb3 (9.
Nf3 {has been just mentioned in the notes to Khalifman - Tukmakov, here are
some details about} Nc6 10. b4 {and now:} Bd6 $5 {is just temporarily giving
up the fight for the central dark squares, while Black would undermine the
b4-pawn at once -} (10... Nd4 11. Qd2 ({White is also determined to control
the d4-square,} 11. Qd3 {follows the same intention -} Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Be7 13.
Rg1 a5 14. b5 {and might be a better version of the leading text, for the
e4-pawn, is overprotected, which is telling after, let us say} d5 15. cxd5 exd5
16. Rxg7 {and in this extraordinary position, Black should probably prepare to
castle and evacuate his king to the queenside without counting the rest of his
pawns on the opposite wing}) 11... Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Be7 13. Rg1 a5 $1 {A timely
counterblow to the capture of this pawn Black is going to castle with plenty
of compensation in the view of White's wrecked structure, while he does not
mind the complications after} 14. Rxg7 axb4 {as well, for instance} 15. Nb5 Bc6
$1 16. Nd6+ $140 Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Nxe4 18. fxe4 Qf6 {(the same sally will come in
reply to 18.?d4 as well)} 19. e5 Qxg7 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Qb8+ Ke7 22. Qd6+ Ke8
