expect to win a pawn with} 13. Rxd6 $6 {- after} f6 {White is needing miracles
like} 14. Rd2 fxg5 15. Qd1 {in order to prevent a loss of material. Black is
staying on top in the sample sequence} Rxf3 $1 16. Qxf3 gxh4 $5 (16... g6) 17.
Qxh5 Bg5 18. f4 Bxf4 19. Qxh4 Bxd2+ 20. Kxd2 Nf6+ 21. Bd3 Qd4 {or 21....h6.})
13... h6 14. Be3 Nhf6 15. Nd4 h5 $1 {A good reaction to the intended 16.g4.
Nevertheless, the opposite-castled kings made me insist on this advance of the
g-pawn, true, under more unfavorable circumstances.} ({Regarding the direct} 
