{The first game is a model for how to play if Black delays the fianchetto of
his queen's bishop.} 1. d4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 2. c4 {
[%emt 0:00:00]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 3. g3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:01]}
4. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} cxd4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 5. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} a6 {
[%emt 0:00:00]} 6. Bg2 {[%emt 0:00:00]} d6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 7. O-O {[%emt 0:00:
01]} Be7 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 8. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} O-O {[%emt 0:00:00] It looks
like Black played a normal opening, but he already has serious problems. The
bishop on g2 is very powerful and there is no obvious way to oppose it or to
otherwise solve the problem of Black's queen's bishop without making new
concessions.} ({The attempt to create early counterplay with} 8... Qc7 {
fails due to Black's serious lag in development:} 9. b3 (9. Qd3 $6) ({or} 9.
Qb3 $6 {is exactly what Black wants: Loss of time and an exposed queen on his
opponent's side.}) 9... d5 $6 10. Bb2 dxc4 11. Rc1 {White just calmly
developed with every moves, and yet Black cannot keep his extra pawn after} O-O
12. Na4 $16) 9. b3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:00:01]} (9... e5 {solves the
problem of Black's queenside development but creates a permanent outpost for
White's pieces on d5. After} 10. Nc2 {, both knights stand ready to exploit it.
}) 10. Bb2 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Nbd7 {[%emt 0:00:00]} ({The attempt} 10... Nc6 {
is met by a common motif:} 11. Rc1 Nxd4 (11... Bd7 12. Nd5 $16) 12. Qxd4 Bd7
13. h3 Bc6 $2 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Ba3 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Bxg2 18. Kxg2
Ne8 19. e4 $16) 11. Rc1 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Rd8 {[%emt 0:00:01] White is fully
developed and it is time to choose a plan against Black's passive setup.} 12.
e3 $1 {[%emt 0:00:01]} (12. e4 {is also sufficient for an advantage, but it
closes the long diagonal and gives Black some hope to achieve b7-b6 and Bb7
shortly.}) 12... Nf8 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 13. f4 {[%emt 0:00:01] White will now
gain space on the kingside with every move, resulting in a kingside attack or
an advantageous endgame.} Rb8 {[%emt 0:00:02]} ({Again, the freeing move} 13...
e5 {creates permanent weaknesses in Black's position.} 14. Nde2 exf4 (14... Rb8
15. h3 b6 16. g4 h6 (16... Bb7 17. Nd5 $18) 17. Ng3 $16 {, followed by g4-g5.})
15. Nxf4 $18) 14. g4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} (14. h3 {may have been even better,
preparing g3-g4 without allowing the following complications. Black lacks
active possibilities to punish White's slow play.}) 14... e5 {[%emt 0:00:02]}
15. Nf5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bxf5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 16. gxf5 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Qc5 {
[%emt 0:00:09]} 17. Qd2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} exf4 {[%emt 0:00:12]} 18. Rxf4 {
[%emt 0:00:01] White still has a clear advantage, and after the following
mistake, Black's position quickly fell apart.} Nh5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 19. Ne4 {
[%emt 0:00:03]} Qa7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 20. Bd4 {[%emt 0:00:03]} b6 {[%emt 0:00:
