{Another game without a black queenside fianchetto. This time White
demonstrates how the space advantage can be turned into a win after an
exchange of queens.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Qc7 6. Nf3
Bxc5 7. g3 Qb6 8. e3 Be7 9. Bg2 (9. g4) 9... a6 10. b3 Qc7 {In a most unusual
way, this 4.Qc2 Nimzo transposed into a Hedgehog position. Again Black has
delayed the development of his queen's bishop and White will exploit that.} 11.
Nd4 $1 {Preventing b7-b6.} (11. O-O $2 b6 $1 12. Bb2 Bb7 13. e4 d6 14. Nd4 {
, with a normal Hedgehog position.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O d6 13. Bb2 $16 Ra7 {
An ugly move, but the only way to oppose White's powerful bishop.} (13... Nc6
14. Nd5 $1 Nxd4 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. exd4 $16) 14. Qe2 b6 15. f4 $1 Bb7 16. g4
Bxg2 17. Qxg2 Qb7 18. g5 ({Playing with the queen's on the board after} 18. e4
{was possible, with a more complicated and also more double-edged position,
resembling an open Sicilian.}) 18... Qxg2+ 19. Kxg2 $16 Nfd7 20. h4 Re8 21.
Rfd1 Rc7 22. Rd2 Nc6 23. Nde2 $1 f5 24. e4 Rf8 (24... g6 25. h5 Bf8 26. hxg6
hxg6 27. exf5 exf5 (27... gxf5 28. Ng3 $16) 28. Nd5 $16) 25. exf5 Rxf5 26. Ne4
e5 27. Nxd6 Bxd6 28. Rxd6 exf4 29. Rf1 Ne7 30. Nxf4 Rb7 31. Nd5 Nxd5 32. cxd5
Rxf1 33. Kxf1 a5 34. h5 b5 35. Ke2 Kf8 36. Bd4 b4 37. Kd3 Ke7 38. Ra6 Kf7 39.
Kc4 Rc7+ 40. Rc6 Rb7 41. g6+ hxg6 42. hxg6+ Ke8 43. d6 Kd8 44. Ra6 1-0

