{Hello dear readers of Modern chess. After a couple of articles about Sicilian
pawn structure, now it is time to move on to a structure which appears after
another opening. The subject of this article will be the English Hedgehog Pawn
Structure. English Hedgehog is very complex and difficult to play opening, for
both sides. In the arising position is important not to memorize long forced
variations, but to be aware of the nuances, tactical and strategical
opportunities. Positions are closed and maneuvering and usually the side who
better understands the pawn structure wins the game. English Hedgehog arises
after:} 1. c4 ({Another move order is:} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7
5. Nc3 e6 6. O-O Be7) 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 3. g3 e6 4. Nf3 (4. Bg2 {This is a
well know inaccuracy.} d5 $1 {and White is unable to stop the following d5-d4})
4... b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 {We put our bishop to opposite White's one on g2.} 6. O-O
Be7 {This is the starting position of the English Hedgehog. What Black wants
to do: of course Black can go for some Queen's Indian positions by playing
d7-d5, but these positions are not subject of our article. In Hedgehog Black
has the following scheme of development: Be7-Nbd7-a6-0-0-Rac8, Rfe(d)8 and
Qc7-b8(a8). This is the ideal development structure, which Black is trying to
achieve. In some variations White forced the game and positions became very
concrete, but in 90% of the cases, Black can achieve this development. The
real fight begins now and I will try to explain you the ideas and typical
motifs in the examples later. White is at a crossroad: They can play 7.d4, 7.
Re1 or 7.b3. After the first one variation, we achieve immediately Hedgehog
position, after second and third Black can stay in our structure or play d5
with some Queen's Indian type of positions.} 7. d4 {is the main option.} (7.
Re1 {The idea of this move is to play first e2-e4 and later d4. Then White can
take on d4 with the Knight, without exchanging his light-squared bishop.} d5 (
7... Ne4 {Trying to equalize immediately.} 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. d3 Bb7 10. e4 O-O
11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 {After this almost forced variations,
we achieve a position with a tiny advantage for White. Many players are happy
to defend this with Black pieces.}) (7... d6 {Inviting our opponent into
Hedgehog territory.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. d4 {We are in one of the main lines in
Queen's Indian.}) 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 {The drawback of this variation is that
the queen is a bit vulnerable here and he should lose a tempo to find another
place for his strongest piece.} (8. Nxd4 {This move will be the subject of our
first game. The exchange of light-squared bishops so early is harmless for
Black according to theory.}) *

