1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nc3 Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{Usually you will face this move when your opponent is not so familiar with
Hedgehog structure or he has no ambition to win the game.} Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qc8 $1
{Important move: We attack immediately the c4-pawn, preparing Nc6 and the
queen is going to take control over the long diagonal.} (9... d6 {We should
mention that now the typical d6 and Nbd7 is a mistake.} 10. e3 {[%cal Rd1f3]
White is preparing Qf3 with control over the important c6-square and over the
long diagonal. Usually after 7.Nxd4 we keep the pawn on d7 and try to play Nc6.
}) (9... Qc7 $5 {Even if it is possible, it is less accurate here, because it
runs into Nb5 in many occasions.}) 10. Qd3 ({The natural} 10. b3 {runs into} d5
$1 {The Knight on c3 is not protected and here the complications are in
Black's favour}) 10... Nc6 {One idea is to exchange the N, another is to win a
pawn with Ne5} 11. b3 {Diagram [#]} (11. Nxc6 {This move leads to a pleasant
endgame for Black.} Qxc6+ 12. Qf3 ({If} 12. f3 {then} Rc8 13. b3 d5 {and Black
is in trouble}) 12... Qxf3+ 13. Kxf3 Rc8 $1 14. b3 d5 15. Nb5 a6 16. Na3 Ne4
17. cxd5 exd5 18. Nc4 Nxg3 19. hxg3 dxc4 20. bxc4 Rxc4 {Black wins a pawn and
later the game in 0-1 (39) Dronjic,S (2178)-Nestorovic,N (2439) Novi Sad 2014})
11... Ne5 12. Qe3 Qb7+ {Important check! Now White should leave the long
diagonal by playing 12Kg1 or weaken his kingside by playing 12.f3} 13. f3 Ng6 {
Usually, g6 is not a bad square for our queenside's Knight} 14. Rd1 O-O 15. Bb2
{It looks like White manages to consolidate his position, but} h5 $1 {Diagram 
[#] This is the first typical idea which I want to show you. Black runs his
h-pawn in order to create weaknesses in White's camp. White has a difficult
choice to make: to stop h5-h4 by playing h2-h4 which weakenes his kingside or
to allow h5-h4. In that game White chose the second option which led to a
disaster.} 16. Qd3 h4 17. e4 Nh5 $1 18. Qe3 Rae8 19. Nde2 f5 20. exf5 exf5 21.
Qd2 Qb8 22. Nd5 Bb4 $1 {Beatiful tactical shot which ends the game.} 23. Qd3 (
23. Nxb4 Rxe2+ $1 {The point of the combination} 24. Qxe2 Ngf4+ $17) 23... hxg3
24. hxg3 Rxe2+ 25. Qxe2 Qxg3+ 26. Kf1 Ngf4 27. Nxf4 Nxf4 28. Qf2 Qh3+ 29. Kg1
Bc5 30. Bd4 Rf6 {Beatiful game which shows us how dangerous can be Black's
attack after h7-h5 0-1 (30) Nei,I-Gurgenidze,B Kharkov 1967} *

