{In this equal position White decides to exchange the light squared bishops,
with an idea later to play Ne4 and to increase the pressure against d6 pawn.
This is a typical idea and can work if White plays now 13.Ng5. Instead of this,
13. Nd2 was played and Black immediately wins the game. The vulnerability of
White's queen on d4 is a very important nuance in the Hedgehog positions
especially after 7.d4 and both sides should be very careful how this factor
affects the position.} 12. Nd2 $2 {Restricts the mobility of white queen
allowing Black to win the material by} e5 $1 {Black's queen does not have any
good square on the board} 13. Qh4 (13. Qe3 {runs into} Ng4 $19) 13... Bxg2 14.
Kxg2 Nd5 {The game is practically over, White is losing a piece.} 15. Nxd5 (15.
Qg4 Nxc3 16. Rc1 f5 17. Qf3 N3e4 $19) 15... Bxh4 16. gxh4 Qxh4 {Black simply
converts his big material advantage.} 17. Bxc5 dxc5 18. Nf3 Qe4 19. Rfe1 Qg4+
20. Kh1 e4 21. Nf6+ gxf6 22. Rg1 Qxg1+ 23. Rxg1+ Kh8 0-1

