{In the previous example it was easy to see that 13.Nd2 was a blunder, but in
this position it is very hard to find out that such a natural move like Rac1
can be a reason to lose the game.} 16. Rac1 $2 {This mistake leads to the loss
of material.} (16. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 16... e5 $1 {After 15 moves of positional
battle, Black goes for a well calculated tactical variation.} 17. Qe3 (17. Qf5
$2 Bc8 $19) 17... Ng4 18. Qxb6 {It looks like White is OK, because after Nxf2
White's position looks nice, but the idea is completely different.} Nxc3 $1 (
18... Nexf2 $143 19. Nd5 $1 Nxd1 $140 20. Nxe7+ Kf8 21. Nf5) (18... Ngxf2 $143
19. Rf1 Nxc3 20. Rxc3 Ne4 21. Rcc1 $13) 19. Rxc3 Rd7 $1 {[%csl Rb6] Playing
for the trap of white queen. This little nasty move decides the game. You
should admit that Black's idea is just blilliant[%cal Ge7d8]} 20. Bh3 Bd8 21.
Bxg4 Bxb6 22. Bxd7 Qc7 {and Black won the game} 0-1

