{As we already saw in the previous examples after complete development, we
should try to open the game. Black has two main ideas to break the centre. One
is b6-b5 attacking the c4-pawn and another is d6-d5.} 21... Red8 $1 {[%cal
Gd8d1] Black removes his rook from the opposition with White`s rooks and
prepares the advance d6-d5. One important rule in English Hedgehog is that
Black should try to put his rook into the opposition of White's queen.} 22. Kg1
d5 $1 23. cxd5 ({In case of} 23. e5 $6 {Black can play} dxc4 $1 ({this is
stronger than} 23... Nfe4) 24. Bxb7 Qxb7 25. bxc4 (25. exf6 $2 Bxf6 26. Nb1 e5
$19) 25... Nh5 $15 ({or} 25... Nfd7 26. f4 Nb8 $15)) 23... exd5 24. e5 Nfe4 25.
Re3 $2 ({White could maintain the balanced position by} 25. b4 Nxc3 26. Bxc3
Ne4 27. Ba1 Re8 ({dubious is} 27... Bxe5 $6 28. Nf5 $1) 28. Nf3 {even here
Black remains with better chances.}) 25... Bxe5 26. b4 Bxd4 $6 ({Was correct} 
26... Bg7 $1 {with possible continuation} 27. bxc5 bxc5 28. Na4 (28. Nde2 $2 d4
$19) 28... cxd4 29. Bxd4 (29. Nb6 $2 {runs into} dxe3 $1 30. Nxa8 exf2+ 31. Kh2
fxe1=Q 32. Qxe1 Bxb2 $19 {and Black has too much material for the queen.})
29... Bxd4 30. Qxd4 Rc4 31. Qd1 Qb8 {With an obvious advantage for Black}) 27.
Qxd4 Ne6 28. Qxb6 {Finally after some adventures, the game ended in a draw.}
1/2-1/2

