13... b5 $5 {When the e4 pawn is not very well protected, the strike b6-b5
always comes into mind. Remember one very important rule: Exchanging b-pawn
for e-pawn favours Black if the queens are on the board. In teh endgame,
White's passed pawns on the queenside are stronger than Black's central
pawns!!!} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. a3 (15. Nxb5 Nxe4 16. Qe2 Rc8 $132) 15... e5 $1 {
Black takes away the d4-square from Nf3 and in such a way solves the problem
with the defense of b5-pawn. The weakness of the d5-square is not so important
in this situation. Black's plan is to play ?c6-?b7 and eventually b5-b4.} 16.
b4 Bc6 17. Qe2 Bd8 $5 {Very typical and strong manoeuvre. Black's dark squared
bishop comes to the important a7-g1 diagonal} ({This is a more active plan
than the continuation} 17... Nb6 18. Nd2 Bd7 19. Rac1 Rc8 20. Bf1 Na4 (20...
Nc4 21. Nxc4 bxc4 $13) 21. Nxa4 Rxa4 $11) 18. Nd2 ({Deserves attention} 18.
Rac1 Bb6 19. Bh3 $5 $13) 18... Bb6 19. Nb3 Re8 20. h3 $6 {Weakens White`s pawn
structure on the kingside. Do you remember how we started to make weaknesses} (
{better was} 20. Rac1 $142 h5 $140 21. Bf3 {With slightly worse, but
defendable position for White.}) 20... h5 $1 {Just in time! This move is much
stronger after including h3.} 21. Bf3 h4 $1 22. Kg2 (22. gxh4 {makes too many
holes in Black's position} Nf8 $44 {[%cal Gf8e6,Gf8g6]}) 22... Nf8 $1 23. Rad1
Ne6 24. Nd5 (24. Qd2 hxg3 25. fxg3 Nd4 26. Nxd4 Bxd4 $36) 24... Bxd5 25. exd5
Ng5 26. gxh4 (26. Qxb5 $2 hxg3 27. fxg3 Qc8 $19 {[%cal Gc8h3,Gc8c2]}) 26...
Nxf3 27. Qxf3 Rc8 28. Rc1 Qb7 29. Rxc8+ Rxc8 30. Rd1 $2 {After this mistake,
White hardly can defend his position.} ({Was necessary} 30. Rc1 Rxc1 31. Bxc1
Qxd5 32. Qxd5 Nxd5 $15 {Black is much better, but still, should show some good
endgame skills to win the game.}) 30... Rc4 ({Also strong was} 30... Rc2 31.
Rd2 Qc8 32. Qd3 Rc4) 31. Bc1 Qc8 32. Bg5 $2 {Loses immediately.} ({More
tenacious was} 32. Bd2 e4 33. Qg3 {when Black continues} Rc2 {and if} 34. Rc1 {
then} Qf5 $1 35. Rxc2 Nh5 $19) 32... e4 33. Qf4 Rc3 34. Bxf6 Qxh3+ 35. Kg1 Rg3+
{This game includes many important strategical Black's ideas: b7-b5 break,
fixing e4-pawn by e6-e5 and h-pawn marsh.} 0-1

